1
00:00:01,079 --> 00:00:05,480
Even if you're a complete beginner in trading,
you must have come across the term "scalping"

2
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:10,099
at some point. The main goal of scalping is
to make a profit through buying or selling

3
00:00:10,099 --> 00:00:16,320
an asset for a very short period of time,
and closing it for a small profit. However,

4
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:21,210
you should be aware that this trading style
will demand a certain amount of time and concentration

5
00:00:21,210 --> 00:00:26,300
and if you aren’t able to dedicate a few
hours a day to this, then this 1-minute scalping

6
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:31,710
strategy might not be the best fit for you.
Now, for this strategy we’ll rely on exponential

7
00:00:31,710 --> 00:00:38,159
moving averages. A single moving average gives
you the general trend of price movement. However,

8
00:00:38,159 --> 00:00:43,120
a lot of traders typically use two or more
moving averages to gain a better feel for

9
00:00:43,120 --> 00:00:48,400
main direction and to trigger more precise
entries or exits in the market. That’s why

10
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:53,930
we’ll use a trio of moving averages to monitor
the short, medium, and long term trend of

11
00:00:53,930 --> 00:01:01,120
a market, and will allow us to estimate the
trend’s intensity from multiple timeframes.

12
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:07,150
So here we have a 1-min chart of EUR JPY,
which displays three exponential moving averages:

13
00:01:07,150 --> 00:01:16,540
the 50, 100, and 150-period averages. The
50-period EMA gives me the short term trend,

14
00:01:16,540 --> 00:01:21,830
the 100- and 150-period EMA’s give me the
medium and long term trends. Of course, this

15
00:01:21,830 --> 00:01:28,430
is my preference. I prefer to use longer term
EMAs, to try to eliminate the inevitable market

16
00:01:28,430 --> 00:01:33,420
noise. Any number of period combinations can
be used, depending on the types of setups

17
00:01:33,420 --> 00:01:39,130
you are looking for and the timeframes you
are trading. So, feel free to use other moving

18
00:01:39,130 --> 00:01:42,500
averages, you don’t have to use the exact
setup.

19
00:01:42,500 --> 00:01:47,500
Looking back at this chart, notice how price
pushed above the three EMA’s and traded

20
00:01:47,500 --> 00:01:54,020
steadily higher, the price staying above the
50-period EMA the entire time. The fact that

21
00:01:54,020 --> 00:01:59,420
all three EMA’s were trending higher at
around forty-five degree angles during the

22
00:01:59,420 --> 00:02:05,740
advance was very bullish. This is the image
we’ll search on our chart, meaning all three

23
00:02:05,740 --> 00:02:12,200
moving averages in agreement, in line, almost
parallel, with strong trend consensus. Right

24
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:18,590
here, the price eventually broke below the
50-period EMA, which signaled short-term weakness,

25
00:02:18,590 --> 00:02:25,760
but bounced off the 100-period EMA before
resuming the uptrend, thereby confirming the

26
00:02:25,760 --> 00:02:31,760
medium and long term strength. Until the price
breaks below the 150-period EMA, the bullish

27
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:35,090
trend will remain intact.

28
00:02:35,090 --> 00:02:39,930
After we identified the main direction, we
need to wait for a pullback. So, we’ll search

29
00:02:39,930 --> 00:02:46,930
for a pullback trade, to pinpoint undervalued
and overvalued entries into established trends.

30
00:02:46,930 --> 00:02:52,650
So our goal is to find opportunities when
price is considered overvalued or undervalued,

31
00:02:52,650 --> 00:02:57,210
as this presents excellent opportunities to
“buy low during uptrends, and sell high

32
00:02:57,210 --> 00:03:01,120
during downtrend”.
The idea of the pull-back trade is to buy

33
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:06,130
the market at a discount during an uptrend,
and sell the market at a premium during a

34
00:03:06,130 --> 00:03:09,489
down trend.
The goal of the pull-back trade is to take

35
00:03:09,489 --> 00:03:15,350
advantage of situations when price is in an
established trend, either bullish or bearish,

36
00:03:15,350 --> 00:03:20,410
and all three moving averages are indicating
the same direction. Any pull-back to the first

37
00:03:20,410 --> 00:03:26,320
or second EMA offers a buying (or selling)
opportunity back in the direction of the established

38
00:03:26,320 --> 00:03:29,740
trend.
This setup is effective because it forces

39
00:03:29,740 --> 00:03:35,370
you to buy below value and sell above value,
while keeping you disciplined to the existing

40
00:03:35,370 --> 00:03:36,739
trend.

41
00:03:36,739 --> 00:03:42,110
Now, how to enter a trade?
So the first step, the most important one,

42
00:03:42,110 --> 00:03:46,670
is to identify the current trend of the market.
I know I’m repeating myself, but i want

43
00:03:46,670 --> 00:03:52,420
this to be crystal clear. All three EMA’s
must be trending in agreement in a bullish

44
00:03:52,420 --> 00:03:58,599
or bearish manner. Ideally, you want to see
all three EMA’s trending at a 45-degree

45
00:03:58,599 --> 00:04:06,060
angle, which identifies a strong trend. However,
any slope ranging from 30- to 60-degrees will

46
00:04:06,060 --> 00:04:12,379
work just fine. The second step involves waiting
for the market to pull back to test either

47
00:04:12,379 --> 00:04:19,409
the 50- or 100-period EMA. Price can close
beyond the 50-period EMA, but you generally

48
00:04:19,409 --> 00:04:27,270
do not want price to close beyond the 100-period
EMA, or to be near the 150 EMA. Once price

49
00:04:27,270 --> 00:04:33,059
tests either of the moving averages, we need
price confirmation. The entry is triggered

50
00:04:33,059 --> 00:04:40,349
when price closes back in the direction of
the current trend, beyond the 50-period EMA.

51
00:04:40,349 --> 00:04:45,129
How to manage the trade. There are many exit
tactics that can be used for the pull-back

52
00:04:45,129 --> 00:04:50,999
trade. Before you select the type of exit
strategy, you should first remember you are

53
00:04:50,999 --> 00:04:57,370
scalping. The room for error is extremely
small. Let me repeat that: margin for error

54
00:04:57,370 --> 00:05:02,129
is very small when you trade with high leverage
while looking for a small profit. With that

55
00:05:02,129 --> 00:05:07,539
in mind, here is what I do when I’m scalping:
• I move my stops to breakeven as soon as

56
00:05:07,539 --> 00:05:13,719
possible. You want to diminish your risk.
You will get stopped out a lot at breakeven,

57
00:05:13,719 --> 00:05:19,180
but from my experience it’s better to have
5 trades in a row with zero profit, than 5

58
00:05:19,180 --> 00:05:25,369
losing trades. That’s the ugly face of scalping,
it’s very unpredictable and any price swing

59
00:05:25,369 --> 00:05:30,759
can hit your stop loss. That’s why I look
to play the breakeven trade when I’m 5-6

60
00:05:30,759 --> 00:05:36,080
pips in profit. You will be frustrated when
you’ll have 5 pips in profit, move your

61
00:05:36,080 --> 00:05:40,069
stop to breakeven, and then the market will
hit your stop loss and will continue in your

62
00:05:40,069 --> 00:05:45,509
initial direction. It will happen. But this
will protect you in the long run.

63
00:05:45,509 --> 00:05:51,110
If you have a bigger risk aversion, here are
other tactics you could use:

64
00:05:51,110 --> 00:05:55,070
• a traditional trailing profit stop.
• a fixed profit target

65
00:05:55,070 --> 00:06:02,159
• exit at the next support and resistance
levels, or at a fib extension, if you trade

66
00:06:02,159 --> 00:06:05,099
with fib numbers.

67
00:06:05,099 --> 00:06:09,669
This chart illustrates a perfect example of
choosing a currency pair during an established

68
00:06:09,669 --> 00:06:17,020
trend. Notice that all three EMA’s are trending
lower at 45-degree angles, which is important

69
00:06:17,020 --> 00:06:22,289
because this is a measurement of trend intensity.
Trading in the direction of an established

70
00:06:22,289 --> 00:06:27,860
trend increases your chances for a profitable
outcome. Now that direction has been established,

71
00:06:27,860 --> 00:06:34,490
we look for price to break above the 50-day
EMA in order to set the stage for a “sell”

72
00:06:34,490 --> 00:06:39,800
scenario. Once price dips above the first
EMA, we look for price to close back below

73
00:06:39,800 --> 00:06:45,349
the 50-period average in order to trigger
a long position, which occurred several times

74
00:06:45,349 --> 00:06:50,809
in this chart. Also remember that you can
use any period moving average you like to

75
00:06:50,809 --> 00:06:56,999
manage your trades! You could back test different
settings, and adapt the period of the EMAs

76
00:06:56,999 --> 00:07:01,210
to fit your style.
Once in the trade, i immediately set my loss

77
00:07:01,210 --> 00:07:06,999
stop below the low of the pull-back i am trading.
Therefore, your stop loss would be beneath

78
00:07:06,999 --> 00:07:11,349
the low of the bar that tested the 50 or 100
period EMA.

79
00:07:11,349 --> 00:07:18,330
